title: Assessment of Safety, Tolerability, and Efficacy of LY3372689 in Early Symptomatic Alzheimer's Disease
description_brief: The purpose of this study is to assess the safety, tolerability and effect of study drug LY3372689 in participants with early symptomatic Alzheimer's Disease

measures.title: Baseline Integrated Alzheimer's Disease Rating Scale (iADRS) Score
measures.description: Integrated Alzheimer's Disease Rating Scale is used to assess whether LY3372689 slows down the clinical decline associated with Alzheimer's disease (AD) compared with placebo. iADRS is an integrated assessment of cognition and daily function comprised of items from the Alzheimer's disease assessment scale-cognitive subscale (ADAS-Cog13) and the Alzheimer's disease cooperative study-instrumental activities of daily living scale (ADCS-iADL). The scale ranges from 0 to 144, where lower scores indicate worse performance and higher score indicates better performance

measures.title: Screening Tau Category
measures.description:
All randomized participants (pts) who have only evaluable Screening Tau category data. Intermediate tau (Low-medium): All pts with screening composite tau PET standardized uptake value ratio (SUVr) \<= 1.46 and a topographic deposition pattern consistent with advanced AD (AD++) or 1.10 \<= SUVr \<= 1.46 and a topographic deposition pattern consistent with moderate AD (AD+).

High tau:All pts with SUVr \>1.46 and topographic deposition pattern consistent with either moderate (AD+) or advanced AD (AD++).

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline to End Time Point in Integrated Alzheimer's Disease Rating Scale (iADRS) (Intermediate (Low-medium) Tau Population)
outcomeMeasures.description: iADRS is a simple linear combination of scores from 13-item alzheimer's disease assessment scale-cognitive subscale (ADAS-Cog13) and the Alzheimer's disease cooperative study-instrumental activities of daily living scale (ADCS-iADL). It is used to assess whether LY3372689 slows down the cognitive and functional decline associated with early symptomatic Alzheimer's Disease, compared to placebo. The iADRS score ranges from 0 to 144 with lower scores indicating worse performance and higher score better performance. Change from baseline was calculated using Bayesian disease progression model (DPM) adjusted for age at baseline, AChEI/Memantine use at baseline, pooled investigator. Data presented are posterior mean with 95% credible interval.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: All randomized participants with baseline or post-baseline data for this outcome with baseline Intermediate Tau level.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline to End Time Point in Clinical Dementia Rating Scale - Sum of Boxes (CDR-SB) (Intermediate (Low-medium) Tau Population)
outcomeMeasures.description: CDR-SB is a semi-structured interview of participants and their caregivers. Participant's cognitive status is rated across 6 domains of functioning, including memory, orientation, judgment/problem solving, community affairs, home/hobbies, and personal care. Severity score are assigned for each of 6 domains; Total score (SB) ranges from 0 to 18. Higher scores indicate greater disease severity. LS Mean change from baseline was calculated using natural cubic spline with 2 degrees of freedom (NCS2) adjusted for fixed effects of NCS basis expansion terms (two terms), NCS basis expansion term-by-treatment interaction, visit (in weeks), investigator site (pooled), age at baseline, AChEI/Memantine use at baseline.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: All randomized participants with baseline or post-baseline data for this outcome with baseline Intermediate Tau level.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline to End Time Point in Alzheimer's Disease Assessment Scale - Cognitive Subscale (ADAS-Cog13) (Intermediate (Low-medium) Tau Population)
outcomeMeasures.description: The ADAS-Cog13 is a rater administered instrument that was designed to assess the severity of the dysfunction in the cognitive and noncognitive behaviours characteristic of persons with AD. The cognitive subscale of the ADAS-Cog13 consists of 13 items assessing areas of cognitive function most typically impaired in AD: orientation, verbal memory, language, praxis, delayed free recall, digit cancellation. The ADAS-Cog13 scale ranges from 0 to 85. Higher scores indicate greater disease severity. LS Mean change from baseline was calculated using natural cubic spline with 2 degrees of freedom (NCS2) adjusted for fixed effects of NCS basis expansion terms (two terms), NCS basis expansion term-by-treatment interaction, visit (in weeks), investigator site (pooled), age at baseline, AChEI/Memantine use at baseline.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: All randomized participants with baseline or post-baseline data for this outcome with baseline Intermediate Tau level.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline to End Time Point in Alzheimer's Disease Cooperative Study Instrumental Activities of Daily Living Inventory (ADCS-iADL) (Intermediate (Low-medium) Tau Population)
outcomeMeasures.description: The ADCS-iADL is a 23-item inventory developed as a rater-administered questionnaire answered by the participant's caregiver. The ADCS-iADL measures both basic and instrumental activities (instrumental activity items 6a, 7-23) of daily living by participants. The range for the ADCS-iADL is 0-59 with higher scores reflecting better performance. LS Mean change from baseline was calculated using natural cubic spline with 2 degrees of freedom (NCS2) adjusted for fixed effects of NCS basis expansion terms (two terms), NCS basis expansion term-by-treatment interaction, visit (in weeks), investigator site (pooled), age at baseline, AChEI/Memantine use at baseline.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline to End Time Point In Brain Tau Deposition as Measured by Flortaucipir F18 Positron Emission Tomography (PET) Scan (Intermediate (Low-medium) Tau Population)
outcomeMeasures.description: Flortaucipir PET imaging was used as a quantitative tau biomarker. Quantitative tau burden was formalized using Standardized Uptake Value Ratio (SUVR) from the following composite brain regions: frontal, parietal, occipital, and temporal lobes and the Alzheimer's disease (AD) neocortical signature. The AD neocortical signature region of interest refers to a weighted Alzheimer's Disease specific neocortical region derived from Multiblock Barycentric Discriminant Analysis. Cerebellar gray matter was used as a reference region to derive an SUVr. Larger SUVR reflects larger tau burden. LS Mean change from baseline was calculated using ANCOVA adjusted for baseline score, age and treatment (Type III sum of squares).
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: All randomized participants with baseline Intermediate Tau level and with baseline and at least one postbaseline PET tau data.

outcomeMeasures.title: Change From Baseline to End Time Point in Volumetric Magnetic Resonance Imaging (vMRI) Measures (Intermediate (Low-medium) Tau Population)
outcomeMeasures.description: MRI scans at baseline and at 76 weeks after the first treatment were used to quantitatively estimate change in brain atrophy. Volumetric MRI (vMRI) parameters were measured in brain regions: bilateral hippocampus, bilateral whole lateral ventricles, and bilateral whole brain. The atrophy was assessed by tensor-based morphometry, which captures volume changes within the deformation map. LS Mean change from baseline was determined by mixed model repeated measures (MMRM) model with fixed effects of treatment, visit, treatment-by-visit interaction, and adjusted for baseline volume, age at baseline.
outcomeMeasures.populationDescription: All randomized participants with baseline Intermediate Tau level and with baseline and at least one postbaseline vMRI data.

adverseEventsModule.description:
All randomized participants who received at least one dose of study drug. Gender specific events occurring only in male or female participants have had number of participants at risk adjusted accordingly.

One death is noted in participant flow for '3 mg LY3372689' arm, while two are reported under adverse events. This is because a participant who discontinued due to an AE later died-counted as "AE leading to death" in adverse events, but only as "discontinuation due to AE" in participant flow.

explanation_target: Reason: The trial tests LY3372689 in early symptomatic Alzheimer's disease; LY3372689 (also named ceperognastat) is an orally available small‑molecule inhibitor of O‑GlcNAcase (OGA) developed to modify tau pathology by increasing tau O‑GlcNAcylation and thereby reducing pathological tau aggregation — a disease‑modifying strategy rather than a symptomatic cognitive enhancer or neuropsychiatric treatment. citeturn1search1turn0search1

Act: Key extracted details — drug name: LY3372689 (ceperognastat); mechanism: O‑GlcNAcase (OGA) inhibition aimed at reducing tau pathology; formulation/route: oral small molecule; trial: Phase 2 study assessing safety, tolerability and efficacy in early symptomatic AD (NCT05063539 / study titled 'Assessment of Safety, Tolerability, and Efficacy of LY3372689 in Early Symptomatic Alzheimer's Disease'). citeturn1search1turn1search0

Reflect: Classification check — because LY3372689 is a small‑molecule OGA inhibitor targeting a core AD pathology (tau), it fits the 'disease‑targeted small molecule' category. Sources used: discovery/translation paper describing ceperognastat (LY3372689) as an OGA inhibitor and its preclinical/Phase 1 data, PET occupancy and PK studies, and the Phase 2 trial record. No evidence it is a biologic, purely symptomatic cognitive enhancer, or a neuropsychiatric treatment, so 'disease-targeted small molecule' is appropriate. citeturn1search1turn0search1turn1search0
explanation_agent: Reason: The investigational drug LY3372689 (ceperognastat) is an orally active small‑molecule inhibitor of O‑GlcNAcase (OGA). Inhibiting OGA increases O‑GlcNAcylation of tau, which is intended to reduce pathological tau aggregation and modify tau pathology in Alzheimer disease — therefore the program is directed at tau biology rather than amyloid, inflammation, neurotransmitters, or purely symptomatic mechanisms. citeturn0search6turn0search8turn0search4

Act: Extracted details and mapping to CADRO — drug name: LY3372689 (ceperognastat); mechanism: O‑GlcNAcase (OGA) inhibition to increase tau O‑GlcNAcylation and reduce tau aggregation; formulation/route: oral small molecule; trial: Phase 2 study NCT05063539 assessing safety, tolerability and efficacy in early symptomatic AD. This mechanism directly targets tau protein pathology, so the appropriate CADRO category is B) Tau. citeturn0search1turn0search0turn0search6

Reflect: Confirmation and alternatives considered — the available sources consistently describe ceperognastat as an OGA inhibitor developed to modify tau pathology; there is no indication the primary mechanism targets amyloid, ApoE/lipids, inflammation, neurotransmitter receptors, or a non-therapeutic diagnostic approach. Thus B) Tau is the most specific CADRO classification. If additional data showed a clear multi-modal mechanism affecting other CADRO domains, one could consider R) Multi-target, but current evidence supports B) Tau. citeturn0search6turn0search4

Web search results used (summaries with citations): 1) ALZFORUM therapeutic entry summarizing ceperognastat (LY3372689) as an O‑GlcNAcase inhibitor developed to reduce tau aggregation in AD. citeturn0search6 2) Clinical trial registry entries for NCT05063539 (Phase 2, Eli Lilly) describing the study title, design, dosing (oral), and purpose (safety/tolerability/efficacy in early symptomatic AD). citeturn0search0turn0search1 3) MedChemExpress and related chemistry/compound summaries describing LY3372689 as an orally active OGA inhibitor suitable for tauopathy research. citeturn0search8 4) A 2023–2024 review of AD clinical trials noting the initiation of a phase 2 trial NCT05063539 for LY3372689 directed at tau pathology. citeturn0search4
